I have reviewed your ticket and what you observed is a well-known behavior of GitLab's file-based Export/Import method. Here's a clear breakdown of the root cause and how to prevent it.
 
GitLab's file export/import maps users between instances by matching public email addresses. When a user on the source instance cannot be matched to a user on the destination instance, GitLab falls back to assigning all contributions to the user who performed the import (in your case, Vishnu Gehlot). This is by design.
 
The matching fails when any of these conditions are not met:
 
Users don't exist on the destination instance - The original authors (e.g., PUNAM ANIL RAJPUT) must have accounts on gitlab.sbi.
Public email not set on the source instance - Each user on gitlab.epay.sbi must have a public email set in their profile (Profile → Edit Profile → Public email). This is different from their login/primary email.
Email mismatch - The public email on the source instance must exactly match the primary email on the destination instance.
Export performed by a non-group-owner - Only the top-level group owner exports all members (direct + inherited). A project maintainer/owner only exports direct project members, so inherited members are missing from the export file. In this case, the owner of the group https://gitlab.epay.sbi/epay must perform the export. Also, see Manual Workaround below.
 
How to Prevent This (for future imports using file-based transfer):
 
Follow these prerequisites before exporting:
 
On the source instance (gitlab.epay.sbi):
 
Have every contributing user set their public email in their profile to match their primary email on the destination instance.
Have the top-level group owner (not just a project maintainer) perform the export, so all member data is included. In this case, perform the export as owner of https://gitlab.epay.sbi/epay.
 
On the destination instance (gitlab.sbi):
 
Ensure all users already have accounts created.
Emails must match exactly between source public email and destination primary email.
An administrator must perform the import.
 
With all the above pre-requisites met, you can perform a re-import of the same project to fix the issue.





